    "texts": [
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Identification features",
            "shortText": "<p>Spreading perennial herb branching from the base into a series of fleshy upright stems that are covered in glandular hairs and often pinkish in colour. The hairy leaves are opposite, narrow and toothed at the tips.</p><p>Flowers yellow and borne in loose groups. Each has an extremely long, slender tube containing five stamens and ending in five long, flat lobes that have a wrinkled or ridged texture. The flowers are clove-scented at night.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_1_10157",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Adult size",
            "shortText": "<p>Plants up to 80 cm tall. Flowers about 15-20 mm across and with tubes up to 28 mm long.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_2_10158",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Distribution",
            "shortText": "<p><u>Global:</u> Endemic to South Africa.</p><p><u>Local/Regional:</u> Restricted distribution between about Saldanha Bay and Cape Agulhas.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_3_10159",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Biology",
            "shortText": "<p>Found only on coastal sands in the Western Cape where it occurs among other scrub which they use for support. Fragrant only at night, suggesting that they are pollinated by moths.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_4_10160",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Food / prey",
            "shortText": "<p>Photosynthetic.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_5_10161",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Reproduction",
            "shortText": "<p>Flowers August to November.&nbsp;</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_6_10162",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Similar species",
            "shortText": "<p>The closely-related Sad tearbush <i>L. triste</i> has broader leaves that are clustered mostly at the base of the stems and has similar shaped, whitish to yellow flowers but these are clustered at the tips of the stems and have down-flexed lobes. The species has a wider distribution from Namibia to the Eastern Cape both coastally and inland.</p>",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_7_10163",
            "longText": null,
            "longTextKey": null,
            "images": []
        },
        {
            "taxonTextType": "Further reading / References",
            "shortText": "Manning, J (2007). Field Guide to Fynbos. Cape Town: Random House Struik. (p. 484).<br><br>Manning, J & Goldblatt, P (2000). South African Wild Flower Guide 7: West Coast. Botanical Society of South Africa (p. 180).",
            "shortTextKey": "taxon_text_8_10164",
